subSubSection.paragraph:
Description:
Small spiders, male total length 1.11– 1.61, female 1.27–1.90. Both sexes similar in general appearance with little interspecies variation (
Fig. 16A–C
): cephalic region of both sexes turret-like, raised bearing AMEs in front, PMEs on top, ALEs and PLEs on its sides; AMEs black and very small, AMEd about half of other eyes, rest of eyes subequal; AER recurved, AME-AME less than AMEd, AME-ALE longer, PER straight, PME-PME equal to PMEd, PME-PLE shorter, ALE and PLE juxtaposed. Many impressed, round pits scattered on carapace and anterolateral surface of chelicerae (
Fig. 18B
). Posterior part of carapace elongated into a tubular-shaped petiole. Sternum continuous with carapace laterally, leaving four openings at each side through which coxae are articulated. In dorsal view four lobes can be distinguished around the leg coxae (
Fig. 16A–C
), but not conspicuous in 

S. longqiensis

(
Fig. 14A
) and 

S. yangmingshana

sp. nov.
Legs long and slender, without macrosetae. Patella I–IV with one distal short spine (
Fig. 16B
). Tm I 0.17–0.26. Tm IV absent. Female palpal claw absent (
Figs 14E
, 
16D
). Book lung cover almost smooth (
Fig. 12G
). Epiandrous fusules absent in males (studied in 

S. partibilis

, 

Fig. 12H; 

S


. longqiensis, 

Fig. 15H; 

S


. protrudens, 

Fig. 17E; 

S


. retractilis and 

S. wulingensis

, 
Fig. 20E
). Tracheal system consisting of unbranched median and lateral trunks; median pair slightly wider in diameter than lateral pair, extending into prosoma through petiole (studied in 

S. partibilis

; 

S. akihisai

; 

S. longqiensis

; 

S. protrudens

, 

Fig. 16A; 

S


. retractilis, 

Fig. 18C; 

S


. wulingensis, 
Fig. 20A
). Spinnerets (studied in 

S. partibilis

; 

S. longqiensis

; 

S. protrudens

; 

S. retractilis

; and 

S. wulingensis

): ALS with one major ampullate gland spigot and one nubbin, as well as about 12 piriform gland spigots (
Fig. 16E
); PMS with one minor ampullate gland spigot (
Fig. 16G
), cylindrical gland spigot present (
Fig. 20G
) or not (
Fig. 16G
); PLS with four aciniform gland spigots between the two cylindrical gland spigots (
Fig. 16F
); basal part of mesal cylindrical gland spigot slightly larger than distal one (
Fig. 16F
); flagelliform and aggregate gland spigots (‘araneoid triplet’) well developed in females (
Fig. 16F
), reduced to nubbins in adult males (
Fig. 16H
), but present in adult males of 

S. retractilis

(
Fig. 18F
) and 

S. wulingensis

(
Fig. 20F
). Male palpal tibia with one prolateral, two retrolateral trichobothria (
Fig. 21A
). Proximal part of cymbium extending posteriorly and then turning retrolaterally, forming a large excavation and probasal process, protruding out (
Fig. 15A–C
), or hidden (
Fig. 21A
). Small retrolateral process anterior to proximal part of paracymbium (
Fig. 12A
). Paracymbium U-shaped, curved almost horizontally (
Fig. 15B
) or torsion-shaped turning in the middle (
Fig. 21A
) with additional curve at proximal part that articulates with cymbial retrolateral process (
Fig. 21A
). Tegulum with a chitinized triangular structure in retrolateral view, termed here as ‘S 
olenysa
tegular triangle’ (
Fig. 16A
). Distal suprategular apophysis large, extending ventrally in retrolateral view (
Fig. 19A
). Radix usually small, combined with other elements of embolic division (
Fig. 15D
) or even embedded in a large membranous area that connects the basal part of terminal apophysis and lamella characteristica (
Figs 10D
, 
19E
). Terminal apophysis with three free ends, normally the median one larger (
Fig. 7
). Lamella characteristica deeply divided into three well-developed branches, at least one of them, usually the median branch, ribbon like (
Fig. 7
). Embolus short, sclerotized (
Fig. 12F
), translucent (less sclerotized) or totally membranous (
Fig. 19E, F
), without pointed embolus proper. No embolic membrane arising from column, but sometimes embolus with membranous projection, the distal embolar membrane (‘M’, see 
Figs 15F
, 
17D
). Epigynum well sclerotized, encapsulated, hanging at distal end of a long, transversally wrinkled, membranous solenoid (
Fig. 13A
). Solenoid arising from abdomen tegument, twisting and lifting epigynum up in nonfunctional stage (
Figs 8H
, 
13A
; see also 
Tu & Li, 2006b
: figs 28–30). A pair of seams on epigynal dorsal surface; curved (
Fig. 13B
) or straight (
Fig. 14H
), transversal (
Fig. 17G
) or longitudinal (
Fig. 14H
); distal ends served as copulatory openings, proximal ends as fertilization openings. Fertilization ducts directed mesally (
Fig. 8I
).
